#### Ghostly Spirits
*Potion, common*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*Stoppered with the bone of an undead being, This spirit is typically drunk at funerals or times of remembrance. Though the sight of past loved ones brings comfort, there are plenty who lose themselves, clinging to past.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

This bottle of pale-blue liquor holds enough for 16 shots. A faint, swirling mist can be seen hovering above the liquid. When found, a bottle has 2d8 shots remaining.

***A Toast to the Dead.*** You may raise your glass and speak the name of someone who has died. Upon drinking, a silent, ghostly illusion of the named individual appears before you for 10 minutes. The detail and clarity of this illusion is determined by how well you knew this person in life. Strangers appear as a blurry wisp of spectral vapor.

#### Glass Sword
*Weapon (shortsword), rare (requires attunement)*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*Found clutched in the mummified hands of entombed warriors of the Scorpion Desert, these swords seem to resonate with nearby magical forces. How they were made and what purpose they had is unknown. Some theories suggest they were used to ward of an ancient evil that nearly brought the desert tribes to ruin…*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have a +3 bonus to attack and damage rolls made with this weapon.

While holding this sword, you can use an action to cast *dispel magic* with an ability score bonus of +5. The sword regains the ability to do so at dawn.

***Fragile.*** When you roll a natural 1 on an attack roll with this sword, it shatters, dealing 3d8 piercing damage to the target.

#### Infernal Contract
*Wondrous item, legendary*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*You are unsure what material this scroll is made from, Some thin, pale leather perhaps? It is warm to the touch and smells of burnt bones. The small print offers to solve your desperations, but for a high cost...*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

These contracts are used by mid-to-high level devils to broker deals with desirable individuals, though occasionally they can be found by suspiciously lucky individuals. The terms of the deal are clearly laid out, awaiting only a signature in blood. 

Once signed, this contract is forever binding: only a *wish* spell can erase either the benefits or curse of the contract. Eliminating the benefits does not erase the curse, and vice versa; lost benefits cannot be replaced by a new contract, and attempting to duck the terms of the contract by removing the curse gains you the emnity of the Hells, who will take an interest in making a gruesome example out of your soul.

You can only have one contract at a time. There are six types of contract:

1. **Contract of Blood.** You return to the prime of your youth. You also increase your ability scores by up to five points, distributed as you wish. As normal, you can't increase an ability score above 20.
2. **Contract of Knowledge.** You gain the ability to cast *contact other plane* as a ritual, which has a DC 10 saving throw. You also gain advantage on all ability checks using one of the following skills of your choice: Arcana, History, Medicine, Nature, or Religion.
3. **Contract of Patronage.** You gain 50,000 XP, or enough experience to raise your level by one (to a maximum of 20), whichever amount is higher. All levels gained from this experience are applied to becoming a warlock with the Fiend patron. If you are a warlock with another patron, it changes to Fiend. Optionally, you can also trade in any levels you have in for levels in warlock at a one-to-one ratio. 
4. **Contract of Power.** You gain an additional spell slot for each of your spell levels. Alternatively, you may choose three spells from any class that is 3rd level or lower and gain them as once-per-day spell-like abilities.
5. **Contract of Riches.** Within the next few days, you will somehow gain 50,000 gp worth of wealth or one non-legendary, non-artifact item.
6. **Contract of Service.** You gain the ability to cast *find familiar* as a ritual, summoning an imp instead of the normal options. You can also cast *summon greater demon*, summoning a devil instead of a demon, without requiring a material component or expending a spell slot and regain the ability to do so when you finish a long rest. The devil follows your commands without question.

***Curse: Damned.*** The signee has disadvantage on all death saving throws. Upon death, their soul teleports to the contract giver's native plane and is imprisoned within a magic crystal. The signee cannot be resurrected until their soul is freed.

#### Keg of Holding [WIP]
*Wondrous item, rare*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*Flavor text.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

This item appears to be a small barrel, with multiple spouts sticking out at random points along the sides. It weighs considerably less than its appearance would suggest, weighing only 25 pounds regardless of its contents. The keg can hold up to 500 gallons of liquid; for each different liquid poured the top of the keg a new spout appears.

Liquids in the *keg of holding* spoil twice as slow as they would in a regular barrel; liquids also retain the temperature in which they were when poured into the keg until they spoil. If the plug at the top of the keg is opened and turned upside down all liquids will mix and pour out. 

The *keg of holding* is an extradimensional space and follows all rules that would affect a *bag of holding*.

> A keg is most commonly a half-barrel. In 5e terms, it has a capacity of 20 gallons or 2 cubic feet, a cost of 1 gp, and weighs 10 pounds when empty.)

