#### Lucky Blade
*Weapon (any), rare (requires attunement)*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*Everyone thinks they have a lucky item. A lucky copper piece, lucky dagger, lucky hat. But luck is much more fickle than that. Especially magical luck. See, luck is tangible and it truly exists in certain places.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

This weapon has golden four-leaf clovers embossed on its hilt. There is a strange weighting in the weapon's hilt that will occasionally cause a mediocre hit strike true, almost as if the weapon has a mind of its own.

***Lucky Seven.*** This weapon scores a critical hit on a roll of 7 or 20.

#### Midnight Cauldron [WIP]
*Wondrous item, very rare*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*There are many cauldrons used by witches and wise women, but few are as wicked or as powerful as the Midnight Cauldron. The symbols inscribed glow in the darkness of night, it's cold iron belly hungry for sacrifice.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

This cauldron can only be used at night. When filled with boiling water, the heart of a humanoid who has died within the last day can be sacrificed to grant one charge to the cauldron. If the heart was from a humanoid child, it instead gains three charges. The cauldron can only hold up to 10 charges; once dawn breaks, the cauldron loses all charges.

***Boil and Trouble.*** Over the course of one hour, you can expend charges and use the cauldron to brew a potion, creating one of the following based on the number of charges expended:
- *[potion of disguise](#potion-of-disguise)* (1 charge)
- *alter self* (2 charges)
- *enhance ability* (2 charges)
- *elixir of health* (2 charges)
- *potion of superior healing* (3 charges)
- *polymorph* (4 charges)

The potions of 

***Hag's Eye.*** During a full moon, you can use the cauldron to cast *scrying* without expending a spell slot. Once per lunar cycle, you can expend 10 charges to cast *bestow curse* as a 9th level spell on the target of your scrying. Both effects have spell save DC 17.

#### Ms. Bobbin's Umbrella Blade [WIP]
*Weapon (rapier), uncommon*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*The infamous witch known as Ms. Bobbins would disguise herself as a nanny to wealthy nobles, snatching up their children in her carpet bag. When confronted, she would beguile her adversaries with strange songs before running them through with this hidden blade.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have a +1 bonus to attack and damage rolls made with this weapon. When holding it, you can cast *feather fall* or *levitate* on yourself only, once per day.

#### Mudwalkers
*Wondrous item, uncommon*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*These battered old boots seem pretty ordinary until you spot the runes stitched on the inside. The soles are perpetually caked in mud no matter how you clean them. Every homeowner's nightmare.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You ignore difficult terrain created by marshes or mud when wearing these boots.

***Mud Slide.*** You can spend a bonus action to slide 20 feet in a single direction, leaving a trail of thick, slippery mud. The area through which you pass is affected as though through *grease*. The effect remains for 1 minute. The boots can do so three times and regain all expended uses at dawn.

#### Occam's Razor
*Weapon (longsword, dagger), legendary (requires attunement)*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*This weapon has seen better days. Are you sure it will hold up in battle? Seemingly being held together by sheer determination, large fractures have split this blade into numerous shards.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have a +2 bonus to attack and damage rolls made with this weapon.

***Shatter.*** As an action, you can speak the command word and slam the weapon down, causing it to break into pieces. Ten Tiny pieces of the blade are animated, as through *animate objects* (deals slashing damage, no concentration required). If the blade pieces are ever more than 120 feet away from you or reduced to 0 hit points, they crumble to dust.

When the blade is shattered, you are left with a hilt with enough shards to act as a +2 dagger in your hand. You can end the shatter effect as a bonus action, at which time all remaining pieces return to the dagger. If at least 3 pieces return, the dagger becomes a shortsword, and if at least 6 pieces return, it becomes a longsword again.

The weapon can use this ability once and regains the ability to do so at dawn, at which point any destroyed pieces reform.

#### Orb of Plagues
*Wondrous item, very rare (requires attunement)*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*Painful rashes and boils appear on your skin when you touch this glass orb. You notice sickly green fumes leak out of a small crack on it's surface.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

The orb has 10 charges and regains 1d6 + 3 charges per day. If there are no charges, roll a d20. On a 1, it shatters (see below).

***Spells.*** While holding the orb, you can cast *detect poison and disease* as a ritual. You can expend one or more charges to cast the following spells: *ray of sickness* (1 charge), *ray of enfeeblement* (2 charges), *stinking cloud* (3 charges), *blight* (4 charges), *contagion* (5 charges).

***Plague Cloud.*** As an action, you can smash the orb onto the ground, destroying it and releasing a plague cloud in a 35 foot radius sphere. All creatures within this area are affected by one random disease from the *contagion* spell, against a spell save DC equal to 10 + the remaining number of charges.

\pagebreak

#### Potion of Disguise [WIP]
*Potion, uncommon*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

When you drink this potion, your appearance changes into a random member of your own race, as though through *alter self*. If you mix into the potion a piece of another humanoid, such as a lock of hair, you instead take on their appearance.

The potion lasts for 1d4 hours, after which the effects gradually fade over 10 minutes; the GM rolls the duration in secret. If you mixed in a piece of a humanoid from another race, roll a d20 when the potion expires; on a 1, some part of the transformation permanently remains, such as colored skin or pointed ears. If you mixed in a part of a non-humanoid, the potion fails and you permanently gain part of that creature's physical appearance. These effects can only be removed with *greater restoration* or similar effects.

This potion looks and tastes like thick mud, bubbling slowly. Upon mixing parts of another creature in, the potion changes to a unique color, flavor, and consistency based on the target creature.

#### Potion of Liquid Luck
*Potion, very rare*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

*A banned substance in all organized competitions, along with other methods of cheating.*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

This potion is the color of molten gold and large drops leap like goldfish from its surface, never spilling. When you drink this potion, you are incredibly lucky for the next 24 hours, gaining advantage on all attack rolls, saving throws, and ability checks. 

For the next seven days, whenever you make an attack roll, saving throw, or ability check, first roll a d6. On a 1, you have disadvantage on that roll. This duration doubles for each previous *potion of liquid luck* you have consumed. If you drink another *potion of liquid luck* during that time, it instead affects you like a *potion of poison*, except that the poison's initial damage is 5d6, its save DC is 15, and the poisoned condition can only be removed by a *greater restoration* effect.

